description.text: The kids wanted snow cones for dessert tonight, and we were horrified to discover that we were missing a critical part (the "Locking Cap") that attached the handle to the grater. You turn the knob that extends through the middle to lock it into place. Original machine instructions: http://www.hasbro.com/common/instruct/SnoopySnoConeMachine.pdf Update 8/4/12: Includes a 3mm hole on the handle. Stick a piece of filament through it to help keep the parts together securely and make it easier to turn.

1) Print. 
2) Assemble as shown in photos. 
3) Make sno-cones again without having to buy a new machine.
4) Hug smiling kids and ask them to remind Mommy what a great investment the 3D printer was.

  • Attach the housing to the front panel using two small screws
  • Fit the front panel back into the quad

Included the OpenSCAD source file in case you need to afjust any of the sizes, although the TLV600 is fairly standard in size

description.text:
First of all credit to the author Mizukii and thanks for permission to post a remix. I have posted this remix because I was asked for my files.

I modified the original model in various places with Zbrush to thicken up areas that were too thin when printed. For example the elbow guards barely contacted the forearms. Also areas like the ankle and knees. Doesn't detract from the model but gives added strength. I deemed this necessary after I printed the legs from the source model and they broke at the ankle and knees.

Also, using Google images, I assembled the wing pieces in Zbrush (Dynamesh and Decimation Master) to create a single printable object comprising both wings. Also put the wings in place at the back of the torso in Zbrush and Boolean subtracted to leave nice slots for gluing the printed wing assembly into the printed torso. It is a tight fit so it might require a little sanding or filing depending upon your printer performance.

I also assembled the Overwatch and Pharah nameplates, circular pedestal and stand in Zbrush (Dynamesh and Decimation Master) to create a watertight part that could be printed in one pass without gluing.

At 100% scale total figurine height is about 210 mm.

description.text: In our house we use these Method refillable foam-soap dispensers, which are great except that my kids have a hard time pushing them straight down. On a tiny sink ledge like in the picture, this means the soap dispenser is constantly ending up on the floor. So, I designed this little holder for the dispenser. It mounts on the wall with two drywall anchors, and also rests on the sink ledge, so there is lots of strength underneath it. There is also has a little hole for stray water to drain into the sink. It fits this kind of bottle, which has a diameter at the base of just over 80mm: http://www.amazon.com/Method-Foaming-Hand-Wash-Waterfall/dp/B004O61852 The filament ridges will collect a bit of grime, but it easily wipes clean. You might want to put a bit of caulking around the rim where it rests on the wall, if your kids are as messy as mine. See the print instructions for details. Designed in Autodesk Fusion 360.

I printed on Replicator2 at medium-quality defaults, with support. The STLs are oriented in the way that I found best to print at. The mounting bracket should be printed with all the contact surfaces off the print bed. It will probably warp a little bit, but in the orientation I provide, this will not cause any problems for the fit. The small inset on the back of the bracket is to provide space for the front rim of the drywall anchors, so that you can still get it flush with the wall. The tray has a small lip around the hole underneath, which is there to make sure that the water will drip and not run along the base. This does mean that the bottom will be covered in support.
which means the bottom will be covered in very short support that is hard to break off by hand. I use a wood chisel to slice support off large flat areas like this, it works great. Once the parts are printed, you may have to lightly sand the bracket to get it to slide into the slot on the back of the tray. Do not try to force it in, or you won't be able to get it back out!! A safer option is to screw the bracket to a block of wood for testing the fit. The cavity is slightly angled, so it will have stairsteps. Printing at high quality might help with this. You can sand it if you want, but in my experience the water still runs down-hill. I tested the dish in various orientations, here are the problems. With the cavity facing downwards, Makerware will may to bridge it (!). With support, cleaning the cavity will take a long time, and you will want to sand it smooth so that water can flow. With the whole thing vertical (ie in the rear face), any warping will mean that it will be very hard to fit into the bracket, and it will not be flush against the wall. Also the filament lines will be stair-steppy right at the most visible part, whereas printed flat they look reasonably nice.

description.text:
If you ever had to replace the connector of a CAT6 cable, you know what to do with this Thingy. Other than CAT5 the CAT6 cable has a separator in the middle.

This keeps the twisted pairs separated, which is a good thing.

But...

If you use cheap (but good quality) connectors these cables are hard to manage. The copper is a little bit thicker and the pairs can slide inside the cable. So if you try to keep the pairs the same length, you might end up a bit fustrated. If you lose your grip on the cable the pairs will immediately have different lengths. description.text:
I wanted to print a E3D-V6 Bowden Carriage Mount for my 2020 V-slot X-Axis conversion of the AM8.

I liked Tech2C's E3Dv6 Bowden X-carriage mount v2 for Prusa i3: https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1632847. It is compact and allows unobstructed view on the nozzle. So, I converted it to fit the OpenBuilds V-Slot Mini Gantry.

I based the conversion to thaug29's E3D-V6 Carriage Mount for OpenBuild Mini V-Gantry: https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2612065. I also used his BL-Touch mount (this is his unedited STL file I include in "my" thing). I just printed it mirrored to put it on the left of the extruder. The base plate provides mounting holes on either side. I plan to use the ones on the right as anchor points for cable-ties for the heater cable.

Finally, I converted xSiNx's E3DClamp with integrated Fan Mount: https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2493738 to fit the extruder Base (I also include an unedited clamp in case you don't want it combined with the fan mount)

I could not find a "real" metal V-Slot Mini Gantry: https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:69004 , so I printed one as well, customizing it with holes for 5mm nuts on the back (I also include their unedited STL file in case you need it)

Please don't mind the messy cables in the photo. :-) I'm in the process of tiding everything up. I'll upload better pictures when it's done.

Howto build:
First of all, glue the 2 parts for the LED Grid together on the inside.
As a diffuser I used high quality and thicker paper - it’s important that you don’t see the fibres when you hold it against bright light like normal printer paper.
Then smear the flat side of the LED grid with glue stick and glue the paper onto it.
this is best done where Awtrix will end up. Due to high temperature and humidity fluctuations, the paper can warp slightly.
Then put the 2 housings parts together and, if necessary, fix it with a little glue. Solder 2 cables to the power jack and screw it to the housing. You can then continue directly with the remaining wiring. the LDR can be plugged through one of the upper 5mm ventilation holes. When everything is ready, place the diffuser facing down and place the LED matrix on top of it, which should fit perfectly in the groove and Press the housing onto the LED Grid. Then turn everything on the back and attach the front frame. Finished

electrical note:
This flexible LED matrix contains 256 RGB LEDs arranged in an 8×32 grid. The panel can draw as much as 15A if all LEDs are set to bright white, which is NOT recommended, but it can overheat at currents well below this. To avoid overheating, I recommend using the panel in a way that keeps the current draw under 5.5 A, which should generally keep the temperature of the LEDs below their 70°C maximum rating.

title: Minimalist magnetic stir plate for an 80mm fan

description.text:
Just got done with this device. It's a pretty minimalist design, no hardware required other than six magnets measuring 8x2mm, part #67488 at Harbor Freight and a magnetic stir rod. I used a touch of super glue on either side of the contact points for the fan because I found the fan would just throw them off if it spun up too fast.

Using 5-6 volts to power the 12v fan seems about right. That might change depending on the viscosity of your substrate.

The mount was printed in PLA with two shells, two top and bottom layers and 10% triangular infill. I added a fillet to each corner to match up better with the fan after I printed mine. It friction fits pretty well to the screw holes.

The magnet holder portion was printed solid as a failed attempt at balancing. Doesn't really matter much though, it's not spinning at very high RPM.

This will be included as part of another project I'm doing, but for now, it will be posted as its own thing.

I've included small cutouts to make them easier to remove from the build plate.
Toss the magnets in and go to town.

Many outdoor adventures take place in mountainous areas, so I created these modular cliffs to create flexible, fast, and easy vertical areas for your games! Designed to print and paint easily, and toss on the table as needed! Designed to work on 1" grid or gridless boards, and include lots of variety and realistic rock faces.   • 2 stairway piece variations
  • Corner pieces
  • End / step-down pieces
  • Cave entrance pieces
  • Crevasse pass piece
  • Round wooden door entrance piece
  • Dwarven mine/hall entrance piece
  • Ledge piece
  • Cage
  • Demon pedestal
  • Worship shrine
  • Skull pillars
  • Sacrificial altar
  • Rough stone pedestal & bowl

These models print with no supports, and paint up quickly and easily with a few base coats and a wash. For ultra fast painting, print in black PLA, prime with 80% coverage gray, then dry brush with lighter gray. All examples in the pics are printed @ .2 layer height and 5% infill.

description.text:
MARK, CUT, DRILL, SAND and RUN with your 3d printed rc car!!!

Emmm... what?¿? with a piece of plastic?¿?

Ok, this is a tool to help you measure and mark, drill and hold your dogbones and pins while sanding them.

To use it, you should go as follows:

  • First of all would be to mark a 5mm piano wire to be cutted at the desired length. For this, use the convex surface to place the piano wire starting in the "0", then use the "ruler" to position your pen tip at the desired length or nearest one. You can do this always by hand with a ruler and a pen, but you should be able to rotate the piano wire over the convex surface while holding the pen in position to draw a circle around the wire. After that you can introduce it in the 5 mm hole to hold it with the 2 M3 screws in place to help you cut it. The selector button must be near the side to allow the 5mm wire to go through the tool.

  • Second, after cutting the 5mm piano wire to the desired length (must be dogbone extreme to extreme distance) you must drill both sides to be able to introduce the pins. For this, you must put the selector button in the "drill position", introduce the cutted 5mm wire from the left side till touching the selector button and then fix its position with the 2 M3 screws.

  • Drilling with the 3mm bit over a 5mm piano wire wont be easy, and if you try it just holding a big drilling machine it will be really hard, also previously marking the place for the pin. So i think i have quite a nice solution: The tool and its two 3x10x4 bearings shoud help you perfectly align perpendicular and centered where the hole must be. The bearings can rotate with the drilling tool and maybe they shoud allow a little of perpendicular force deviation while drilling.

  • One time you have your dogbone with its holes, you must take the 3mm piano wire and mark and cut it twice for each dogbone with the provided 10mm and 12mm depth holes. Introduce the wire in the hole and mark arround it to cut it after that.

  • It's a good idea to sand the "heads" of th main piece trying to give it a half-spherical shape. For doing this you can put the select button in the sanding position and use the thumb button to avoid the dogbone to turn while you push it against a sanding cylinder. You can also introduce your cutted pins in the 3mm or 2mm holes to sand their "heads".

If you can't access 3x10x4 bearings maybe you can use 5x10x4 ones and the provided adaptor. The idea is that the walls of the adaptor or the bearing turns all together, so you shouldn't damage them much.

Needed Material:

  • 2x 3x10x4 bearings or 2x 5x10x4 + adaptor
  • 2x M3 Hex Socket Head 16mm or longer screws
  • Dremel like machine with cutting disk, sanding cylinder and if possible 3mm drill bit.

  • Protection Glasses

If you plan to use this in a MyRCCar config with printed FR diff vases, they should be compatible. A 1/8 center diff also uses 3mm pins but if you don't glue the pins and pray they could get shooted from the car. I made some covers for this 1/8 center diff vases so the pins shouldn't get shooted. If you are interested in this addons please tell me and i'll publish them.

As always, i encourage you to join the MyRCCar Group if you are really interested in the project.

Also, if you are using 02024+converter as center diff. You will need 2mm pins and holes for this side of the dogbone, so maybe you would use the 2mm adaptor for 5x10x4 bearings to use a 2mm drill bit. There is a special 2mm hole to hold the pin while sanding the extremes.

Do the drills over a "martir" table, so, one time you have drill the backpart of the thing you don't drill the floor or something undesired.

This is a handle bar for the Zhiyun Crane handheld gimbal. Read the info for more.
The handles are both right side. You will need to mirror one handle to have a left side. This way you can decide on which side you want to have the trigger.

Welcome!
This is the building guide for a handle bar for gimbals with built in camera remote.

You can start right away or read the instructions, if you want to save a lot of time.
The budget is about 80€, depending on the materials you use.

To include the remote you will need a little bit of experience with soldering. Of course, you can also just print the parts without the cutouts for electronics and not have a remote.

10mm diameter tubes
In my build I used carbon fibre: http://amzn.to/2nUCpna
Depending on the desired width of the bar, you will need between 120 and 150cm. Cut it into 6 pieces of the same length.
Remember: They need to be hollow.

Camera remote
I used this one: http://amzn.to/2EXnHD8
The cutouts and screw holes are specifically designed for this remote. If you don't want to order from Amazon Germany, you can look for similar remotes for the Lumix. I believe they're all the same China products - but no warranty for that.

Button
I bought the button in a local electronics store - offline. Just get a button with a diameter of 9mm and a maximum (inner) length of 30mm.

Screws
To attach the lid and the remotes PCB, you will need a total of 8 M3 screws with a length of 10mm.

Epoxy glue
Use that to attach the tubes to the printed parts. Be sure to use the right glue for your materials.

Attachment screw
This screw will tighten the gimbal to the bar. Look at the centre piece in the Thingiview. I used a screw and a thumb stud from my GoPro accessory kit. If you don't have something like this, I think you will need an M5 screw and bolt. I'd recommend printing a thumb stud so that you can tighten the gimbal without tools.

Jumper cables (optional)
You can solder everything directly to the PCB, but it will be a little bit more maintainable if you use jumper cables to connect everything.

As you can see, I used hot glue to make sure that everything stays in place. In hindsight, this was kinda stupid because now you can't see what I did.

Source: https://www.elektrikforen.de/attachments/microtaster-jpg.13546/

It's very hard to find some guide online but maybe this will be helpful. The remote has a different kind of switch attached, but it works basically the same. Take it off carefully and see how it is connected and I hope everything will add up.
One of the tubes needs to be cut to have space for the cables. Look at the pictures. Both ends need to look like this to leave enough space for the cable to travel through the dedicated channels.

Well, you know what to do. Assemble everything to make it look like on the pictures. Easier said than done, but I believe in you! ;)

If you're new, here are some basic tips to avoid mistakes:

a) Assemble everything before using glue to make sure you have all the parts.
b) While you have everything assembled, test the width of the handle. Is it too wide? Shorten the tubes.
c) Check if the remote is working.

description.text:
Lets be honest. The filament runout sensor is a great addition to the Creality CR-10S, but the factory slide-on mount that Creality supplies sucks. I download and printed several other designs from here and just wasn't happy with the alignment or functionally of them, so I designed my own.

I wanted the filament to be feed straight thru with enough room inbetween to manage any kinks or wobbles in the filament with your hands. I also wanted a better way to reduce friction thru it when near Z=0 and Z = 200+ as the filament is drug thru the horizontal position of the sensor first which is dependent on the way you install the roll (over the top or under). Thats when putting a hinge inbetween seemed like the perfect solution as I run a TUSH spool holder with the extruder feed off the bottom of the spool. I designed this Hinged Filament Sensor Mount so it can be bolted onto the Z-axis brass lead screw nut using factory hardware, then the mount is stabilized to the Z column roller mount right at the hinge. I also designed it so you could run the sensor fully enclosed or with the printed cap to keep crud out. You will need (2) M3X20 screws with (2) M3 hex nuts. Hinge is printed in place.

Please note that after printing you will need to carefully twist the built-in support material off in the same direction as the pivoting hinge. If you use flush cutter on the support material, you may end up splitting the mount in half.

The sensor I designed this around can be purchased here:
https://macewen3d.com/products/cr-10-cr-10-s4-and-s5-replacement-endstop-limit-switch
Which is the same as the factory Creality CR-10S filament runout sensor or Axis stop sensors. My machine actually came with a spare, which made designing/refining it pretty easy.

description.text:
This thing requires some practice in soldering and at least some basic knowledge about electricity.
Unfortunately, I haven't made any photos of the construction.

Short summary:

  1. Solder the four wires from led strip directly to the LED Controller.
    The soldering point has to be on the bottom side of the LED Strip.
    Make sure to lay the wires through the self printed case before.
  2. Glue the LED Strip on the case.
  3. You only need the interior of the Powerbank.
    Solder the positive and negative wires from the RF Controller to the positiv and negative outputs of the "Powerbank Module".
    I've soldered it directly behind the USB Port.
  4. Connect the switch between the positiv wire from the "powerbank module" and the RF Remote Controller.
    Make sure to lay the wires through the self printed cap before.
    Press the switch into the cap.
  5. Insert the battery and test it.
    You can activate the LED with the switch and Change the Colors with the Remote Controller.
  6. Glue the interior of the Powerbank to the bottom of your self printed case.
  7. Put everything inside and screw the cap.

Materials & Equipment:

  • LED Strip
  • LED RF Remote Controller 5v
  • Single 18650 DIY Powerbank
  • 18650 Li-Ion battery
  • 22mm switch
  • Wire
  • Soldering iron
  • Glue
  • Heat shrink tube
  • Multimeter

Bracket to seal off the cutout made for the 05059062AB speakers on Mopar vehicles.

In replacing the speakers in my Jeep's soundbar, I decided to replace the pair (3.5" tweeter/mid; 6.5" woofer) with a single (5.25" coaxial). In doing so, I removed the 3.5" speaker altogether and wanted to seal it off, to create a better sound chamber. This bracket, with a little speaker gasket tape, works well to seal off this cutout.
